Replacing duckbill valves and diaphragms every 1 to 3 months is crucial for maintaining the efficiency and hygiene of your breast pump because - Maintains Suction Efficiency: Duckbill valves and diaphragms are vital for creating a tight seal and maintaining the suction power of the breast pump. Over time, they can become worn or stretched, leading to decreased suction efficiency, which can reduce the amount of breast milk expressed during pumping sessions. - Prevent Contamination: Regular use of breast pumps can lead to the deposition of milk residues or the growth of bacteria and mold in the parts, including valves and diaphragms. Replacing these components frequently ensures that the pump remains hygienic, limiting the risk of contamination of the milk that could potentially harm the baby! ğŸ¤± #foryou #zomeez2 #zomee #fyp #breastpump #momtiktok #pregnantlife #breastfeeding

We get it... It's hard to go with the flow right after giving birth! Many moms wonder when and if their milk will come in! Don't worry, you've been producing colostrum (the first milk) since you were around 20 weeks pregnant! Once your baby and the placenta have been delivered, your body knows that you are now no longer pregnant and those pregnancy hormones rapidly decrease, allowing for the lactation hormones to take over. For most women, this is very easy to recognize; your breasts will feel much fuller, heavier, and maybe even a little warmer and sometimes tender. Your milk will usually come in anywhere between 24 and 72 hours after birth.

How to do Kegels properly Kegel exercise is exercising your pelvic floor by contracting and relaxing the pelvic floor muscles. 1. Empty your bladder 2. Get comfortable either on a chair or lying down 3. Locate your pelvic floor muscles (imagine youâ€™re trying to hold your urine mid-flow but without squeezing your buttocks or inner thighs) 4. Tighten your pelvic floor muscles and count for 3-5 seconds 5. Relax your pelvic floor muscles and count for 3-5 seconds 6. Repeat this 10x - up to 3x per day (morning, afternoon, evening) You might only be able to tighten your pelvic floor for one second to begin with but as you practice it should improve! You can find out more about the Elvie Trainer on our website. It can help you make sure youâ€™re doing Kegels correctly (30% do it incorrectly). It guides you through each exercise on an app and gameifys the experience. #elvie #kegel #kegels #pelvicfloor #pelvicfloorexercises
